Thought_Process: This mechanism is an immediate-acceptance (final admissions) process, so getting into a top choice requires applying there in the exact step it is still available. In Step 1, Nursery_A will receive applications from Parent_A (you) and Parent_D (who ranks it second but is applying to Nursery_C first), while Parent_B applies to Nursery_B and Parent_C to Nursery_D. Nursery_A’s priority order is Parent_B > Parent_D > Parent_A, so if Parent_D applies to Nursery_A in any later step while A is still open, you would lose. The best way to maximize your outcome is to apply to Nursery_A in Step 1 to secure it immediately (since Parent_B is not applying to Nursery_A in Step 1). Any strategy that does not put Nursery_A first risks losing it permanently and ending up with a lower-ranked option. After that, listing remaining schools in true-preference order is optimal because later steps only matter if you are rejected earlier.

Because admissions are final each step and nurseries that fill in Step 1 disappear, the key is to secure the best attainable nursery by applying where I have the strongest chance in Step 1. If I apply to my true #1 (Nursery_B) in Step 1, I lose to Parent_A (higher priority at Nursery_B) and then in Step 2 I cannot apply to Nursery_D because it will already be filled in Step 1 by Parent_C (who applies there first). By instead applying to Nursery_D in Step 1, I still lose there (to Parent_C), but then in Step 2 Nursery_B is still available (it filled with Parent_A at Nursery_A in Step 1, not at Nursery_B), so I can apply to Nursery_B and be admitted (I have higher priority than any other Step-2 applicant there). This yields Nursery_B, my top true choice, so I rank Nursery_D first and Nursery_B second; the remaining options follow my true preferences.

With final admissions each step, the key is to secure a seat in Step 1 at the best nursery where I can actually win priority among Step-1 applicants. If I apply to Nursery_D first, I lose to Parent_D (who ranks D last but could be forced there later only if D stayed open; however D will fill in Step 1 because Parent_A applies to A, Parent_B to B, Parent_D to C, Parent_E to C, leaving me as the only Step-1 applicant to D, but D’s priority list puts Parent_D and Parent_E above me—yet they are not applying to D in Step 1, so I would be admitted if I apply to D in Step 1. Any strategy that delays applying to D risks D being taken by someone else in Step 1 if they change choices (they won’t) or leaving me to compete later when only rejected parents apply and some nurseries are already closed. Therefore, I should rank Nursery_D first to lock in my top choice immediately; the remaining order can follow my true preferences since they will not be reached if I get D.

Because admissions are final immediately (an immediate-acceptance/Boston mechanism), the key is to apply first where you can actually win given others’ first choices and each nursery’s priority order. If you apply to your true #1 (Nursery_C) in Step 1, you lose to Parent_C (higher priority at Nursery_C) and Nursery_C becomes unavailable anyway because it will fill in Step 1. Nursery_A is also unattainable in Step 1 because Parent_B applies there first and has top priority. Nursery_B is the best strategic first choice: in Step 1 only Parent_B applies to Nursery_B, but Nursery_B’s top priority is you (Parent_D), so you would be permanently admitted. This yields your best achievable outcome under this procedure. The remaining order follows your true preferences among the remaining acceptable options.

This mechanism is final-at-each-step: if you apply to a nursery in a step and are the highest-priority applicant among that step’s applicants, you are permanently admitted and cannot later switch. So you should avoid applying early to a “safe” lower-choice nursery if there is a realistic chance to win a higher-choice nursery in a later step when it is still available. Step 1 outcomes among others: Parent_A applies Nursery_A, Parent_B applies Nursery_B, Parent_C applies Nursery_D, Parent_D applies Nursery_C. Each of those nurseries will permanently admit that applicant (each is the only applicant there), so Nursery_A, Nursery_B, Nursery_C, Nursery_D all fill in Step 1 and become unavailable. The only nursery left for later steps is Nursery_E. Therefore, regardless of what you list first, in Step 1 you would be competing only if you also apply to an already-contested nursery; but each contested nursery’s priority list ranks you below the current applicant (e.g., Nursery_C ranks Parent_D above you; Nursery_B ranks Parent_B above you; Nursery_A ranks Parent_A above you; Nursery_D ranks Parent_C above you), so you would be rejected. Since only Nursery_E remains available after Step 1, the best achievable outcome is to ensure you apply to Nursery_E as early as possible among remaining available options (Step 2). Any Step-1 choice is equivalent (you will be rejected), so keep your true top choice first and place Nursery_E second to secure it in Step 2.

With final admissions each round (Boston mechanism), the key is to apply first to the most preferred nursery where I can actually win given others’ first choices and each nursery’s priority. After securing the best attainable early seat, the remaining order can follow my true preferences among the rest.
